title.narrative: Government Debt & Infrastructure Finance - Madagascar. Government Debt and Infrastructure Finance - Madagascar. Government Debt and Infrastructuer Finance - Madagascar

description.narrative: Support the Ministry of Finance and Budget in 1. broadening the investment base for domestic government securities in order to ensure adequate domestic financing for budget deficits and investment and 2. promoting greater clarity of debt management objectives and build a capacity to better manage and mitigate debt portfolio risks.. Project is in development. The goal of this project is to broaden the Government of Madagascar's financing options and reduce the risks of unpredictable foreign borrowing by improving the Ministry of Economy and Finance's (MEF) capacity to transparently issue and manage public debt in the primary market for local currency denominated government securities. Project activities will focus on 1) transitioning to market based auctions to improve transparency and reliability of funding and 2) enhancing the MEF's capacity to issue and manage the debt portfolio.. Project has been discontinued.. Project is not yet started. The objectives of the TA engagement in Madagascar includes: mobilization of domestic savings to broaden the government's funding sources, extension of the maturity profile of government securities to reduce risk and development of a more liquid government securities market to support transparent price discovery and increased capital investment.

owner-org.narrative: The federal government of the United States

description.narrative: The U.S. government seeks to help Madagascar consolidate its democratic gains and begin addressing the root causes of poverty, which leave it ranked as one of the poorest countries in the world. According to the World Bank, more than 92 percent of Madagascar's population survives on less than two dollars a day and 77 percent live in extreme poverty. U.S. assistance will provide support in the areas of environment, democracy and good governance, and peace and security. Continued investments in health and food security activities will build upon successes and accelerate progress towards ending preventable child and maternal deaths, preventing malaria, as well as promoting a stable, resilient Malagasy society.
